+TASK: Step 4 follow-up polish and safety fixes
+
+GOAL
+
+Refine the Step 4 policy layer so that:
+
+1) mode-none fallback to VLAN 1 never bypasses existing access↔trunk mode-change protection
+2) auto-detach for VLAN delete-in-use interacts correctly with tagged_set / untagged_set semantics
+3) warning objects become structurally consistent
+4) list-building paths use deterministic deduplication
+5) default fallback VLAN 1 is represented by a named constant
+6) policy flag naming is unified by renaming:
+   allow_vlan_delete_in_use -> allow_vlan_delete_in_use
+
+This is a correctness + consistency follow-up to Step 4.
+Do not redesign the policy model itself.
+
+SELECTED OUTCOME
+
+After this task:
+
+- mode-none fallback still maps to VLAN 1
+- but the resulting effective state must still be subject to the existing mode-change safety rules
+- deleting a VLAN in use with allow_vlan_delete_in_use=True must work safely and deterministically even when the target VLAN currently uses set-style membership semantics
+- warnings must have a consistent machine-readable structure
+- duplicated port lists / VLAN lists must be deduplicated before final use
+- the default fallback VLAN is represented by a named constant
+- user-facing/API/docs naming must use allow_vlan_delete_in_use consistently
+
+STRICT NON-GOALS
+
+Do NOT:
+- redesign Step 1 canonical model
+- redesign Step 2 membership engine
+- redesign Step 3 dual syntax merge
+- redesign Step 4 core policy decisions
+- remove VLAN 1 fallback policy
+- weaken dual syntax conflict detection
+- change None vs [] semantics
+
+FILES TO MODIFY
+
+Primary:
+- src/napalm_jtcom/driver.py
+- src/napalm_jtcom/utils/vlan_membership.py
+
+Likely:
+- src/napalm_jtcom/utils/device_diff.py
+- src/napalm_jtcom/utils/port_vlan_input.py
+- src/napalm_jtcom/model/config.py
+- maybe src/napalm_jtcom/model/vlan.py only if docs/types need updates
+
+Ansible:
+- ansible/action_plugins/jtcom_config.py
+- ansible/library/jtcom_config.py
+- galaxy/bronweg/cgiswitch/plugins/action/jtcom_config.py
+- galaxy/bronweg/cgiswitch/plugins/modules/jtcom_config.py
+
+Docs:
+- README.md
+- galaxy/bronweg/cgiswitch/README.md
+- examples where old flag name appears
+
+Tests:
+- tests/unit/test_vlan_membership_apply.py
+- tests/unit/test_port_vlan_input.py
+- any tests mentioning allow_vlan_delete_in_use
+- add/update targeted tests as described below
+
+PART 1 — RENAME allow_vlan_delete_in_use TO allow_vlan_delete_in_use
+
+RATIONALE
+
+Current override flags are:
+- allow_port_mode_change
+- allow_untagged_move
+- allow_vlan_delete_in_use
+
+The third name is inconsistent with the "allow_*" pattern.
+Rename it for naming consistency.
+
+REQUIRED CHANGE
+
+Rename all public, internal, and documented references:
+
+- allow_vlan_delete_in_use -> allow_vlan_delete_in_use
+
+This includes:
+- driver optional_args
+- function parameters
+- action plugin pass-through
+- module docs
+- Galaxy copies
+- README / examples
+- warning messages / hints
+- tests
+- any structured output keys if present
+
+BACKWARD COMPATIBILITY
+
+Implement backward-compatible alias support for one transition period if feasible.
+
+Preferred behavior:
+- new name: allow_vlan_delete_in_use
+- old name: allow_vlan_delete_in_use still accepted as legacy alias
+- if both are provided:
+    - fail clearly, OR
+    - prefer new name and emit warning
+Pick one and document it.
+Recommended: fail clearly if both are provided.
+
+If alias support is too invasive, at minimum do a clean rename consistently everywhere.
+But prefer alias support if low-risk.
+
+Required docs note:
+- "allow_vlan_delete_in_use is deprecated; use allow_vlan_delete_in_use"
+
+TESTS
+- new flag works
+- old alias works if retained
+- providing both names behaves as specified
+
+PART 2 — ENSURE MODE-NONE FALLBACK DOES NOT BYPASS MODE-CHANGE PROTECTION
+
+CONTEXT
+
+Current Step 4 policy maps desired mode==none to access VLAN 1.
+This can implicitly turn:
+- trunk -> access
+
+That transition must still be subject to the existing access↔trunk policy.
+
+REQUIRED BEHAVIOR
+
+Given:
+- current_per_port
+- desired_per_port (after canonical membership ops)
+- mode-none fallback to VLAN 1
+
+The final effective desired state after fallback must still be checked against:
+- existing access↔trunk mode-change protection
+
+This means:
+- if a port was trunk
+- and after fallback it becomes access VLAN 1
+- then existing mode-change rules still apply:
+    - default apply: fail unless allow_port_mode_change=True
+    - check mode: warning only
+
+IMPLEMENTATION REQUIREMENTS
+
+1) Review the current planning order in vlan_membership / driver.
+2) Ensure fallback to VLAN 1 happens before final mode-change detection,
+   OR ensure mode-change detection is rerun after fallback.
+3) There must not be any code path where:
+   - desired mode becomes none
+   - fallback silently rewrites it to VLAN 1
+   - trunk→access change slips through without allow_port_mode_change
+
+Preferred implementation:
+- compute desired_per_port from canonical membership
+- apply mode-none fallback transformation
+- then run:
+    - mode-change detection
+    - changed_ports / changed_vlans / desired_port_vlan
+- not the other way around
+
+Required tests:
+A) current port is trunk with only tagged VLAN 20, no native
+   desired removes tagged 20
+   fallback maps to VLAN 1
+   result is trunk->access
+   default apply must fail unless allow_port_mode_change=True
+
+B) same scenario in check mode
+   warning only
+
+C) same scenario with allow_port_mode_change=True
+   success
+
+D) access port losing last membership and mapping to VLAN 1
+   access->access
+   should not require allow_port_mode_change
+
+E) ensure warning type(s) clearly indicate both:
+   - fallback occurred
+   - mode-change policy applied if relevant
+
+PART 3 — FIX allow_vlan_delete_in_use INTERACTION WITH tagged_set / untagged_set
+
+CONTEXT
+
+When deleting a VLAN still in use, Step 4 currently augments desired canonical input with:
+- tagged_remove
+- untagged_remove
+
+This can interact badly with set-semantics if the same VlanConfig already contains:
+- tagged_set / tagged_ports
+- untagged_set / untagged_ports
+
+Potential problems:
+- conflicting semantics
+- accidental violation of set-vs-add/remove validation
+- unclear precedence
+
+REQUIRED POLICY
+
+If a VLAN is marked absent and allow_vlan_delete_in_use=True:
+- the policy layer is allowed to detach the VLAN from ports automatically
+- this auto-detach must be deterministic and compatible with canonical model validation
+
+RECOMMENDED APPROACH
+
+Do NOT blindly append tagged_remove / untagged_remove onto existing set-based fields.
+
+Instead, for each VLAN marked absent and still in use:
+
+Option A (preferred):
+- construct a separate policy-layer effective detach plan that does not mutate the original VlanConfig into an invalid mixed set/remove object
+- e.g. augment the effective desired canonical data using fresh VlanConfig instances for deletion policy only
+
+OR
+
+Option B:
+- if mutating existing VlanConfig, then:
+    - if tagged_set/tagged_ports present, convert to an equivalent effective remove-capable representation first
+    - same for untagged_set/untagged_ports
+    - ensure final VlanConfig remains internally valid
+
+The simplest safe rule is:
+- do not mix *_set/*_ports with *_remove in the same object
+- if policy augmentation needs removes, materialize a fresh config object containing only the effective removal operations needed for deletion
+
+REQUIRED BEHAVIOR
+
+Examples:
+
+A) VLAN 20 is absent, currently tagged on ports 5 and 6
+- allow_vlan_delete_in_use=True
+- effective detach plan removes VLAN 20 from ports 5 and 6 before delete
+
+B) VLAN 20 is absent, currently untagged on port 3
+- allow_vlan_delete_in_use=True
+- effective detach plan removes untagged VLAN 20 from port 3 before delete
+
+C) Existing desired input includes tagged_set or untagged_set for VLAN 20
+- no invalid set/remove mixed config may be produced
+- either:
+    - conflict clearly, OR
+    - cleanly materialize effective removal logic
+Recommended: since state=absent dominates, materialize dedicated effective removal logic for delete policy and avoid invalid mixed objects
+
+IMPORTANT
+
+This must not weaken dual syntax conflict detection.
+If the user simultaneously says:
+- VLAN 20 absent
+- and another input path adds membership back to VLAN 20
+that remains a hard conflict.
+
+Required tests:
+A) VLAN absent + current tagged usage + allow_vlan_delete_in_use=True
+   works and does not create invalid mixed set/remove config
+
+B) VLAN absent + current untagged usage + allow_vlan_delete_in_use=True
+   works
+
+C) VLAN absent + set-style desired data on same VLAN
+   behaves deterministically and validly
+   choose and document exact behavior
+
+D) dual syntax conflict still fails even with allow_vlan_delete_in_use=True
+
+E) check mode warning remains accurate
+
+PART 4 — UNIFY WARNING OBJECT STRUCTURE
+
+GOAL
+
+Warnings should be consistently machine-readable.
+
+Current warning objects likely vary by case.
+Unify them.
+
+REQUIRED WARNING SCHEMA
+
+Use a consistent structure as much as practical:
+
+{
+  "type": "<warning_type>",
+  "entity": "port" | "vlan" | "policy",
+  "port_id": <int or null>,
+  "vlan_id": <int or null>,
+  "message": "<human readable message>",
+  "hint": "<optional hint>",
+  ... case-specific fields ...
+}
+
+Minimum required common fields for all warnings:
+- type
+- entity
+- message
+
+Recommended additional common fields:
+- port_id (when applicable)
+- vlan_id (when applicable)
+- hint (when applicable)
+
+CASE-SPECIFIC WARNING TYPES
+
+At minimum normalize:
+- untagged_move
+- vlan_delete_in_use
+- mode_none_mapped_to_vlan1
+- existing mode-change warning type (either preserve current name or standardize it too)
+
+EXAMPLES
+
+untagged move:
+{
+  "type": "untagged_move",
+  "entity": "port",
+  "port_id": 3,
+  "vlan_id": null,
+  "message": "Port 3 would move untagged VLAN from 20 to 30.",
+  "hint": "Set allow_untagged_move=true to allow this change.",
+  "current_untagged_vlan": 20,
+  "desired_untagged_vlan": 30
+}
+
+delete in use:
+{
+  "type": "vlan_delete_in_use",
+  "entity": "vlan",
+  "port_id": null,
+  "vlan_id": 20,
+  "message": "VLAN 20 is still in use.",
+  "hint": "Set allow_vlan_delete_in_use=true to auto-detach and delete it.",
+  "affected_ports_tagged": [5, 6],
+  "affected_ports_untagged": [3]
+}
+
+mode-none fallback:
+{
+  "type": "mode_none_mapped_to_vlan1",
+  "entity": "port",
+  "port_id": 5,
+  "vlan_id": 1,
+  "message": "Port 5 would otherwise have no VLAN membership and was mapped to access VLAN 1.",
+  "hint": "",
+  "mapped_vlan": 1,
+  "reason": "policy_default_vlan1_fallback"
+}
+
+REQUIRED TESTS
+- warning objects for all policy cases include required common fields
+- apply/check outputs remain stable and understandable
+
+PART 5 — DEDUP LISTS BEFORE FINAL USE
+
+CONTEXT
+
+Some policy augmentation paths append port IDs or VLAN IDs into lists.
+This can produce duplicates.
+
+REQUIRED CHANGE
+
+Wherever policy code builds:
+- tagged_remove
+- untagged_remove
+- warning port lists
+- affected port lists
+- changed_ports if recomputed in policy helpers
+ensure the final values are:
+- deduplicated
+- deterministically sorted where ordering matters
+
+Preferred helper:
+- small utility like _merge_sorted_unique(values, extra)
+or
+- sorted(set(...))
+
+Be careful not to destroy None vs [] semantics:
+- only dedup concrete lists
+- do not coerce None into []
+
+PART 6 — INTRODUCE CONSTANT FOR DEFAULT FALLBACK VLAN
+
+GOAL
+
+Replace raw literal `1` in policy fallback code with a named constant.
+
+REQUIRED CHANGE
+
+Add a constant in an appropriate module.
+Recommended name:
+- DEFAULT_FALLBACK_VLAN_ID = 1
+or
+- POLICY_DEFAULT_VLAN_ID = 1
+
+Use this constant in:
+- mode-none fallback logic
+- warning metadata
+- docs/examples if generated programmatically
+- tests where useful (optional)
+
+Do NOT over-engineer this into configurable user input in this step.
+It remains a fixed policy constant.
+
+PART 7 — DRIVER / API WIRING
+
+Update all relevant call paths so that:
+
+- allow_untagged_move is parsed and passed through
+- allow_vlan_delete_in_use is parsed and passed through
+- legacy alias allow_vlan_delete_in_use is handled as specified if you choose to support name migration
+- warnings remain available in check and apply results
+- naming is consistent in:
+    - driver optional_args
+    - set_vlans(...)
+    - apply_device_config(...)
+    - action plugins
+    - module docs
+    - Galaxy copies
+    - README/examples
+
